node.text:
When #DuaLipa answered rapid-fire questions atop a mechanical bull for W last summer, we did not anticipate the exercise to serve as training for her music video, ‘Love Again,’ in which she stars as a line-dancing, bull-riding cowgirl. To see the progress the pop superstar has made from rookie to rodeo clown, visit the link in our bio. 
-
Director: @shayanasadi
W MAG VIDEO: @_a_b_g, @michael_beckert, @tilden.bissell, @rppr 
Special Thanks to @bigskystudios

@danielkaluuya’s Oscar acceptance speech will go down in history as one of the Academy Awards' most memorable moments. Not only did the actor, who won Best Supporting Actor for his portrayal of Fred Hampton in #JudasandtheBlackMessiah, mortify his mother—“My mom met my dad. They had sex. It’s amazing!”—he also profoundly addressed the push for racial justice. “There’s so much work to do guys,” he told the star-studded crowd. “And that’s on everyone in this room, this ain’t no single man job.” Back in 2018, the London native spoke with W about racism in the UK and the US. Three years later, the work continues.
-
Directed by Lynn Hirschberg
W MAG VIDEO
W magazine Vol. 1 2018, Best Performances

Today’s superstars make their names on @Twitch. The livestreaming platform, which Amazon purchased in 2014, now hosts close to 30 million average daily visitors, up from 17.5 million before the pandemic hit. This boom has resulted in an entire generation of young people who view @tsm_myth, @DrLupo, @Pokimanelol, @loserfruit, @gmhikaru, @alexisayeee_ and @nigelsylvester as mainstream celebrities with the influence and clout typically reserved for professional athletes and pop stars.

“People that are original are figuring out how to work within the system but at the same time kind of making their own system.” Watch @adamcharlaphyman, @annasui, @akeemouch, @aurorajames, @evanmock, Dan Colen (@skyhighfarmhudsonvalley), @honeynailz and @lailacooks—some of the talented creatives featured in our latest issue—describe originality in three words, who they think is original (family members included), what being a leader means to them, and who’s inspiring them right now.

node.text:
W has always been—and always will be—a must-read, on screen and off. From Working Girl to Gossip Girl, Kim Kardashian to Marissa Cooper, the magazine has had its fair share of pop culture mentions over the decades. Here, some of the most iconic. Note to Carrie Bradshaw: We’re going to have to side with Berger on this one. We have no issue with scrunchies.
-
Video: @brian__lynch @pier59studios

Natalia Dyer (@nattyiceofficial) as Tommy Shelby from ‘Peaky Blinders’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 

“This season has been quite a different journey,” Dyer says of #StrangerThings fourth season. “It’s bigger, it’s darker, and it’s gonna be great.”

More at the link in our bio.

#NaomiAckie as Arabella from #IMayDestroyYou | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 
“We need more shows like this!” the Master of None star says of Michaela Coel’s groundbreaking series. “Not just about consent, but about many things that we are still arguing over the subtleties of. The discussion outside of this show was very rich, and that’s what I enjoy—watching TV shows that you can have a rich conversation about afterwards. That’s when the best stories are told.”

More at the link in bio. 
-
Photography: @naomiwongo

Matthew Rhys (@moveablefeastny) as Ernest Hemingway from Ken Burns’s ‘Hemingway’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 

“Three-and-a-half years ago I saw on eBay that a boat was on sale,” the Emmy-nominated star of @perrymasonhbo says. “It was a Wheeler Playmate and I knew Hemingway had a Wheeler Playmate. I bought it and restored it over three-and-a-half years and I painted it the same colors as Hemingway. That’s the boat I took the picture on. That was my ode to Papa.”

More at the link in bio. 
-
Photo by Matthew Rhys

@katemara as Emma Lynnwood from ‘ZeroZeroZero’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 

“I’m always attracted to challenging roles. That was the draw,” Mara says of playing Claire in @ateacherfxonhulu. “I certainly have my issues with a lot of choices that she makes, but to me, that’s much more exciting to play than it would be to play someone who’s doing all of the right things.”

More at the link in our bio.
-
Photo by @drewescriva

node.text:
@johnstamos as Elvis from ‘Elvis: The Comeback Special’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

Stamos, who turns 58 today, found hope watching his idol Elvis during the early days of the pandemic. “I always go back to what’s comfortable, musically, especially,” the ‘Big Shot’ star says. “I love Elvis Presley so I watched the 1968 ‘Comeback Special’ again. At the end of it, there’s a song called ‘If I Can Dream.’ When he started singing it I just started crying. It was right after Bobby Kennedy had been shot and Martin Luther King Jr. He felt like, I can’t just be singing about girls and shaking and hound dogs, I have to plug into what’s happening in the world and the country.”
-
Photography: @roberttrachtenberg
Styling: @molly_levin

@madisonlintz as Fleabag from ‘Fleabag’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“She’s trying really hard,” the @boschamazon star says of Phoebe-Waller Bridge’s #Fleabag. “I don’t think I’m that big of a screwup, I really don’t, by no means. She just seems so lost in the world, and living in L.A. it’s so easy to feel like that. There are things that are going good in her life, there’s just still that thing that she’s missing. I think, in a lot of ways, every human has that journey.”

More at the link in our bio.
-

@danedehaan as The Priest from ‘Fleabag’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“Part of its genius is saying, two seasons and we’re done,” Dehaan, the star of #LiseysStory says of #Fleabag. “That restraint, to tell the story you want to tell and know when it’s over, is amazing. I don’t need closure. Life goes on and I’m more than happy to not know what happens to them.”

Link in bio for more.
-
Photo by @christianhogstedt

node.text:
@phoebedynevor as Alex Levy from ‘The Morning Show’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 

“I love her,” the #Bridgerton star says of @jenniferaniston. “She’s so lovable, but watching her take on a powerful role like in @TheMorningShow was so exciting. It was one of those shows I stumbled across in lockdown. The way it talks about male power and what it means to be a female at the top of their game was something that I thought was very interesting, and very of the time.”

For what to expect from Daphne Bridgerton in the hit series’ second season, head to the link in our bio.
-
Photo by Phoebe Dynevor

node.text:
@savannahwelch as Mare Sheehan from ‘Mare of Easttown’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“Her character wasn’t a pretty version of a detective,” Welch, who plays Barbara Gordon on @dctitans says of Kate Winslet’s Mare. “The young mother [Erin], although she had a very small role, she stole the show for me. Even though I was 27 when I had my son, I could relate to that kind of loneliness and the desperation and feeling a bit...I don’t want to say ostracized, but just because of the new reality, friend groups that weren’t really there yet or didn’t have children yet and couldn’t relate to them anymore.”

At the link in bio, the @dctitans star discusses playing the beloved DC Comics character who’s become a symbol of empowerment for both feminists and the disability community.
-
Photography: @toddvwolfsonphoto
Photo Assistant: William McKinney

node.text:
@chiaraaurelia as Miriam ‘Midge’ Maisel from ‘The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“It was definitely a shock,” the @cruelsummer star says of her hit series’ surprise ending. “I was kind of the sleuth of the cast, always trying to put all the pieces together, see what information I could gather. It took us quite a long time to discover it.”

Read on at the link in our bio.
-
Photography: @kleefeldphotography

@lilireinhart as Beth Harmon from ‘The Queen’s Gambit' | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows. 

“I’m a sucker for a period piece,” says the @thecwriverdale star. “And I liked watching a young girl become an adult—have her life completely change in just a few years. I relate to that.”

More at the link in bio.
-
Photo by Lili Reinhart
